(88, 2, 1, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>\n<response>\n	<a key="cname">Ondrej</a>\n	<a key="cmail">aaa</a>\n	<a key="cmessage">There is a thread on here regarding using 3 or O2 mobile broadband ''dongles'' in with an iPhone 3G sim cacd so as to get 12 months unlimited broadband access in a computer or laptop.\r\n\r\nI''ve read through all 47 pages and still can''t get my dongle/sim working properly so I thought I''d ask for help here as that thread seems to have died.\r\n\r\nI have the Huawei E160 O2 branded dongle which was already unlocked but I have replaced the O2 connection manager software with Mobile Partner.\r\nI have an iPhone sim which I have activated. I''ve also activated the ''top-up'' card.\r\nIf I use the settings most commonly recommended here -\r\nStatic APN - payandgo.o2.co.uk\r\nUser - payandgo\r\nPassword - payandgo\r\nAuthentication Protocol - PAP\r\n\r\nI just get an error message &quot;error 619&quot;\r\n\r\nIf I change the APN to ''dynamic'' I can connect but can''t reach any web pages.\r\nThe same happens if I use a static APN setting of m-bb.o2.co.uk\r\nor mobile.o2.co.uk\r\nI''ve tried so many combinations of APN/user/password over the last 24 hours my brain is frazzled!\r\nFrom this and other forums I''ve seen users recommend user names of..\r\nmobileweb\r\n02web\r\nand o2bb\r\n\r\nand passwords of..\r\npassword\r\nPassword\r\nvertigo\r\nVertigo\r\npayandgo\r\netc\r\n\r\nSome give the ''619 error'' and others let me connect but not reach web pages. I would call o2 tech support but as I don''t own an iPhone that''s probably not a good idea!\r\nAAAAAARRRGGGHHH!\r\n\r\nAny help/advice would be much appreciated.\r\nPete</a>\n</response>', '2010-02-02 00:12:28', 0, NULL),
(89, 2, 1, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>\n<response>\n	<a key="cname">Ondrej</a>\n	<a key="cmail">aaa</a>\n	<a key="cmessage">&gt;&gt; PeaNut wrote:\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; I''ve just bought a pay as you go iphone and HAD to buy a pay as you go\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; sim\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; as part of the deal (robbers) so i now have a spare 12 month unlimited\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; date\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; iphone sim card and a unlocked o2 dongle , can i just stick the iphone\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; sim\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; into my dongle and will it work ????\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; i still have the original software on my laptop for the dongle when i\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; did\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; have mobile internet with o2 , what setting if any do i need to change\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; and\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; will it basically be user name Vertigo and the password for password\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt; ?!!?!?\r\n&gt;&gt;\r\n&gt;&gt; The SIM that came with my dongle had these settings\r\n&gt;&gt; APN: m-bb.o2.co.uk\r\n&gt;&gt; user: o2bb\r\n&gt;&gt; pass: password\r\n&gt;&gt; which I changed to\r\n&gt;&gt; APN: payandgo.o2.co.uk\r\n&gt;&gt; user: vertigo\r\n&gt;&gt; pass: password\r\n&gt;&gt; for the iPhone SIM to work.\r\n&gt;\r\n&gt; thank you , what software should i download to control the dongle , ??? do\r\n&gt; i just use the original o2 software i got with my dongel as i used to pay\r\n&gt; for the service so all the software is still on there.\r\ncheers that worked a treat </a>\n</response>', '2010-02-02 00:16:14', 0, NULL),
(90, 2, 1, '<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>\n<response>\n	<a key="cname">Ondrej</a>\n	<a key="cmail">aaa</a>\n	<a key="cmessage">I went to the post office and got my hands on the Huawei E160G with my reduced contract, and so far I am very pleased with it. The modem itself is a large USB stick, very comparable in size to a cigarette lighter. What is interesting is that the electronics can now be packaged in such a small kit, why aint they producing mobile phones of this size?\r\n\r\nMy first step was to get it working on Windows, I plugged in the modem on my old Windows PC and followed the numerous (and strange) online prompts to setup the software. After a lot of beeping, detecting new hardware and other jiggery pokery, I was presented with the Three Modem Manager application. The modem manager is a simple too that enables you to run the dialup connection through the modem. I whipped open the setup manual which informed me that no other setup was required bar setting up the software. So I clicked Connect\r\n\r\n and it failed?\r\n\r\nAccording to the tool I had to check my settings to see if theyre correct. This is a fresh setup of the tool, why would I need to check the settings when Threes own guide mentions theres no setup needed. After 10-15 minutes poking around in the settings menu I finally threw in the towel. Sod it, I wanted to run this thing on Linux anyway so why am I putting myself through the pain?\r\n\r\nLinux is, well, the way it was supposed to happen. I plugged in the stick and straight away I had numerous devices available, the CD-ROM drive for the drivers, the MicroSD reader, and the tty ports for the actual GSM modem. At this time I could of gone the route of setting up Gnome PPP and related tools to dialout to the provider and start using my new fancy net connection, but Id heard that Network Manager 0.7 had the features to use 3G/GPRS built in without any extra settings. I decided to investigate the new version of Network Manager.\r\n\r\nAfter much digging around on the tubes, I finally found a Debian repository containing a build of the lastest Network Manager SVN. A little apt pinning and installation later I had the new version of the tool install. I browsed the existing menu and found a new option: Auto connection to 3G/GPRS , I selected the option and it connected.\r\n\r\nI have to have a little moment to reflect here, Mobile Broadband is a new fad at the moment for most telecoms providers worldwide, so you would expect the Linux software support to be a little sketchy and buggy, but as it turns out the Linux method is alot simplier and easier to use. Im not sure if I was missing anything obvious in Windows, but isnt this stuff just supposed to work?\r\n\r\nSo, signed on to 3G I decided to give it a run for its money. Im running these tests at 1:08am so it maybe a little bias, as I doubt many people would be actually using the APs at this time. I seem to be getting a variable speed of about 1-2mbps, and 150kbps upstream, not bad at all for a mobile provider. The documentation mentions that you should expect up to 2.5mbps, not the 7.2mbps advertised on some sites, all in all Three do a good job of pre-warning you that the speed on the box is not always what you get.\r\n\r\nSo far Im happy with it, Ive had a few minor issues with the stick not registering on the network but Im not sure if this was down to my settings or just a small outage. Ill post a guide in the next few days on configuring Debian up for Network Manager 0.7 and setting it up to work with the E160G.</a>\n</response>', '2010-02-02 00:19:26', 0, NULL),
